				\begin{document}$$PT{S}_{site}=\frac{2\times ({\rm{number}}\,{\rm{of}}\,{\rm{shared}}\,\mathrm{DBL}{\rm{\alpha }}\,{\rm{types}}\,{\rm{in}}\,\mathrm{sites}\,1\,{\rm{and}}\,2)\,}{{\rm{number}}\,{\rm{of}}\,\mathrm{DBL}{\rm{\alpha }}\,{\rm{types}}\,{\rm{in}}\,\mathrm{site}\,1+{\rm{number}}\,{\rm{of}}\,\mathrm{DBL}{\rm{\alpha }}\,{\rm{types}}\,{\rm{in}}\,{\rm{site}}\,2}$$\end{document}PTSsite=2×(numberofsharedDBLαtypesinsites1and2)numberofDBLαtypesinsite1+numberofDBLαtypesinsite2Thus, a PTS score is the ratio of the number of shared DBLα types between two sites and the sum of DBLα types in both sites. A comparison was performed to evaluate the effect of distance (“birds flight” distance and transit/road distance) on DBLα type sharing between sentinel sites. “Birds flight” distance between the sentinel sites was calculated using Google Maps (https://www.google.com/maps/preview) and transit/road distance was calculated using the Via Michelin Maps and Routes application (http://www.viamichelin.com). Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient was calculated to evaluate the trend and was performed using IBM SPSS (Version 22) software.
